{
  "text": "Our conclusions are similar to other critically ill pediatric (1,2,13) and adult [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] populations, which show an independent association between AKI and mortality. A large meta-analysis of \u03fe20,000 adult patients by Ricci et al. (18) showed adjusted relative risks of death of 2.4, 4.2, and 6.4 for mild, moderate, and severe AKI, respectively (p \u03fd 0.0001 for all). Our study found a similar increase in the likelihood of death with AKI, but we did not find increased mortality with increasing AKI stage. This could be explained by a) the association of baseline SCr levels in neonates initially reflecting maternal SCr, b) relatively high death rate in those with AKI classification 1 compared with other populations that could be related to early mortality (before AKI class 2 could be documented), or c) lack of documentation of transition from stage 1 to 2 due to lack of daily SCr in most of infants.",
